practice.question:
A retailer runs everything on one normalized PostgreSQL OLTP database. The checkout path needs fast point queries, but analysts also run growing ad-hoc reports that scan the whole orders history, slowing checkout.

OLTP schema (system of record):

```
CREATE TABLE customers (id BIGSERIAL PRIMARY KEY, name TEXT, country TEXT, signup_date DATE);
CREATE TABLE products (id BIGSERIAL PRIMARY KEY, name TEXT, category TEXT, unit_price NUMERIC(10,2));
CREATE TABLE orders (id BIGSERIAL PRIMARY KEY, customer_id BIGINT REFERENCES customers(id), created_at TIMESTAMPTZ);
CREATE TABLE order_items (order_id BIGINT REFERENCES orders(id), product_id BIGINT REFERENCES products(id), quantity INT, price NUMERIC(10,2));
```

Analysts ask questions like: total revenue per category per month, and revenue per customer country. Your task: decide where these analytical queries should run, and design the schema and load process for that target so the analytical workload does not touch the checkout path. Explain which system is the system of record and which is derived data.
